{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01WndMoie4sTrRzcvXyTtXEk","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the root cause clearly. From the early logs of crdb-cluster-0 (when it started 5 minutes ago), there's a critical DNS error:\n\n```\nfailed to start gossip client to ‹crdb-cluster-1.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local:26257›: initial connection heartbeat failed: grpc: ‹connection error: desc = \"transport: error while dialing: dial tcp: lookup crdb-cluster-0.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local: no such host\"›\n```\n\nThe error says \"lookup crdb-cluster-0.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local: no such host\" - but it's trying to connect to crdb-cluster-1! The error is coming BACK from crdb-cluster-1 when crdb-cluster-1 tries to connect back to crdb-cluster-0 using the advert\n\nised address. So crdb-cluster-0 advertises itself as crdb-cluster-0.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local, but when crdb-cluster-1 tries to resolve that DNS name, it fails. The issue is with the advertised address - when crdb-cluster-0 restarts, it tells other nodes to reach it at that hostname, but the DNS resolution is failing on the receiving end.\n\nLooking at the actual logs, node 1 can see the gossip network fine (all 3 nodes are visible), but it's continuously failing liveness heartbeats with context deadline exceeded errors. This suggests the node can communicate for gossip but is timing out on liveness writes, which could indicate a recovery issue or a quorum problem. The logs from crdb-cluster-1 showing `[n3,s3]` activity confirm it's node 3. So the real issue is that node 1 (crdb-cluster-0) restarted recently and is stuck with liveness heartbeat failures—it can gossip with peers but can't complete the liveness writes. I need to figure out if this is a temporary state that'll resolve itself or if there's something deeper blocking the node from fully rejoining the cluster. The liveness heartbeat failures suggest node 1 can't write to the NodeLiveness key—likely a Raft consensus issue where nodes 2 and 3 hold the leases and node 1's writes are timing out. But the cluster is already initialized and running, so the real problem might be that crdb-cluster-0 restarted recently with DNS errors, and now it's struggling to rejoin properly. db-cluster-0 was deleted and recreated, so its persistent data might be lost, which could explain why the liveness record is on a different epoch than the other nodes. Let me check the PVCs to see if the data actually persisted through the pod recreation. The real question is whether all three nodes are actually healthy and accessible for SQL operations, since nodes 2 and 3 seem to be working fine despite node 1's liveness failures.\n\nThe issue might be that when crdb-cluster-0 was recreated, its hostname resolved differently than expected—possibly to just `crdb-cluster-0` instead of the full FQDN—so it advertised an incorrect address that other nodes can't reach. But the gossip logs show all three nodes are connected and communicating, so the real problem seems to be isolated to liveness heartbeats rather than a complete network isolation.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":14885,"cache_read_input_tokens":41159,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":14885},"output_tokens":19,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9f494416-6771-4774-b77c-fe46c3f66807","uuid":"ead12ec5-53ed-4a0e-96cd-8fee00c82d44","request_id":"req_011Ccb3kB7yo6ss1nYr1rDbe"}
