{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Q5oQTS5spj9viKgx11oUZE","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the situation is changing! Node 3 (crdb-cluster-1) just went from `is_live: true` to `is_live: false` as well. And node 1 has been `is_live: false` for a while.\n\nThe cluster seems to be having serious issues. The liveness heartbeat failures are cascading. Let me check:\n1. Are all pods still running?\n2. What are the resource constraints?\n3. Is there a specific issue with the persistent volumes?\n\nActually, let me look at this more carefully. The error \"disk write failed while updating node liveness: interrupted during singleflight ‹engine sync:0›: context deadline exceeded\" earlier suggests disk I/O issues.\nSince this is a kind cluster running on Docker, the underlying storage is probably tmpfs or Docker overlay, which could be causing these performance problems. But wait—the liveness timeouts are different from what the task describes. The task mentions \"join/advertise errors,\" but we're seeing liveness heartbeat failures instead. Let me go back to the early logs from crdb-cluster-0 and look more carefully. The critical error was the DNS lookup failure when crdb-cluster-1 tried to connect back to crdb-cluster-0, which suggests an advertise address issue.\n\nSo crdb-cluster-0 advertised itself as `crdb-cluster-0.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local`, but that DNS entry wasn't available yet when crdb-cluster-1 attempted to resolve it. The task description and KARMA documentation mention a certificate-rotation scenario where the init command runs before the container is ready, but this is actually about TLS bringup in stage 02. Looking at the working directory path, this is a KARMA run for a cockroachdb-tls-bringup case, and it might be running in insecure mode.\n\nThe cluster appears to be initialized already—`cockroach node status` returns data with node IDs 1, 2, 3—but 