{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DK2XJfwUH7uvo7ozZeGxNS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Node 2 (crdb-cluster-2) has \"slow heartbeat took 28-29 seconds\" and \"heartbeat failed on epoch increment\". This is a SERIOUS issue - the heartbeat is taking 28-29 seconds! The 3-second timeout triggers and the heartbeat fails, but the underlying write is taking 28-29 seconds.\n\nThis is much worse than a simple resource contention issue. Something is specifically wrong with node 2's liveness writes.\n\n\"Heartbeat failed on epoch increment\" means:\n1. Node 2's liveness record expired (because it couldn't write in time)\n2. Another node tried to take over node 2's leases\n3. Node 2 is trying to increment its epoch to reclaim its liveness\n4. But the epoch increment write is taking 28-29 seconds!\n\nWhy would a write take 28-29 seconds? In CockroachDB, the `/System/NodeLiveness` range is a critical system range. If there are ongoing issues with this range (e.g., no leaseholder, Raft election in progress), writes can block for a long time. But nodes 1 and 3 are successfully heartbeating, so the liveness range is working for them. The question is why node 2 specifically is experiencing these massive write delays.\n\nOne possibility is that node 2's lease transfers are getting stuck, creating a cascade where other nodes try to take over its leases, which then blocks its own liveness updates. This could be a CockroachDB bug or severe resource contention that's not self-resolving after 28 minutes. I'm considering whether I can restart just node 2's pod since the constraint only forbids recreating the entire cluster. that nodes 1 and 3 are succeeding with slower heartbeats, so it's not just a general Raft issue. If node 2 were the leaseholder for NodeLiveness, we'd expect to see all nodes struggling equally, but instead node 2 is uniquely slow. This suggests node 2 might be having trouble with its own heartbeat write specifically, possibly due to being overloaded or having local I/O contention on this single-node kind cluster.\n\nLet me shift focus and check a few things: whether restarting the problematic pod helps, what resources each pod is actually consuming, and whether node 2's \"heartbeat failed on epoch increment\" error after 59 minutes of uptime points to a different underlying issue than what nodes 1 and 3 are experiencing.\n\nLooking at the restart history, node 2 also had a restart 49 minutes ago, similar to node 0. The readiness probe failures show both crdb-cluster-1 and crdb-cluster-2 are having trouble responding to health checks on their HTTP endpoints, which suggests the nodes themselves might be struggling or unresponsive rather than just having liveness record issues.\n\nLet me trace back through pod 2's logs from the beginning to understand what actually happened when it first started up.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1720,"cache_read_input_tokens":85877,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1720},"output_tokens":30,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9f494416-6771-4774-b77c-fe46c3f66807","uuid":"6318e7a6-bea3-4fe2-84ec-59d2be383249","request_id":"req_011Ccb5G1kckyWgz8XBCRfjH"}
