{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01FPg9AA8KrZRp5Dd1TRXKfM","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The node restarted (crdb-cluster-2 started_at now shows 09:14:41 - the new restart). But it's STILL having the exact same liveness issue:\n- \"slow heartbeat took 29-30 seconds; err=heartbeat failed on epoch increment\"\n- \"failed node liveness heartbeat: context deadline exceeded\"\n\nThis means the problem IS NOT with the pod's internal state - it's persisting even after a fresh pod restart. The issue must be with the CLUSTER's state (the Raft group state for the liveness range).\nThe fact that the epoch increment itself is timing out after a restart is the real clue here. When a node comes back up and finds its liveness epoch was already incremented by another node (which assumed it was dead), it needs to perform an epoch increment to reclaim its liveness record. But if that write is taking 30 seconds, the NodeLiveness Raft group itself must be struggling - likely the leaseholder is experiencing issues or lease conflicts that are blocking writes to that critical range. Let me check which node holds the lease for the NodeLiveness range. Looking at node 2's status, I notice something odd: it just restarted at 09:14:41 and updated its liveness record at 09:16:30 (0 seconds ago), yet it's still marked as not live. That suggests the `updated_at` timestamp might not be reflecting what I think it is—it could be showing the last gossip update rather than the actual liveness record write time.\n\nNow I'm thinking through what \"heartbeat failed on epoch increment\" actually means: when node 2 comes back up, it reads its liveness record with some epoch N, but while it was down another node incremented that epoch to N+1. When node 2 tries to write its next heartbeat, it's attempting to increment from N+1 to N+2, but the Raft write times out at 3 seconds even though it eventually gets accepted after 30 seconds—hence the specific error message rather than just a context deadline.\n\nThe real problem is that by the time the write succeeds 30 seconds later, the liveness record has already expired again (another 9 seconds have passed without a fresh heartbeat), so the node gets marked as not live. This creates a repeating cycle where writes keep timing out and the node can't maintain its liveness status. The 30-second write latency is the core issue, and I'm wondering if it's related to the NodeLiveness range leaseholder having problems when node 2 restarts and tries to reclaim its lease.\n\nBut the deeper question is why Raft writes are taking 30 seconds at all on a local kind cluster—that should be nearly instant. My suspicion is that there's a pending, uncommitted proposal blocking the Raft group, which would happen if a previous proposal timed out at the client level but was already committed in the log. New proposals would then be stuck waiting for that pending one to resolve. Looking at the error pattern, the \"heartbeat failed on epoch increment\" message suggests the epoch increment itself is what's failing. The write itself took 28 seconds before failing, which is strange since a failed ConditionalPut should return immediately if the condition isn't met. This suggests the write was queued behind other operations in the Raft pipeline. Looking at the bigger picture, the real problem is that this kind cluster is severely resource-constrained—running three CockroachDB nodes in containers on a single machine creates massive CPU and IO contention, leading to those extreme Raft write latencies and liveness heartbeat timeouts.\n\nBut stepping back at the task requirements: the cluster does accept SQL connections on node 0, all three nodes are visible in the cluster status, and initialization has already completed. The current liveness issue is separate from the initial join/advertise errors that resolved at startup.\n\nI should try adjusting the liveness configuration with longer heartbeat timeouts, or investigate which node holds the lease for the liveness range to ensure it's stable enough to coordinate the others.\n\nThe real issue might be that after node 2 restarted, the liveness range lost its previous leaseholder and now needs to elect a new one, but if that election is slow or contested, it could explain why writes are timing out at 30 seconds.\n\nLet me step back and focus on what actually matters: the cluster is initialized and SQL is working, so I should verify the three nodes are healthy and accept that this kind cluster might have inherent performance constraints that cause liveness oscillation. Before giving up, though, I should check if there's unnecessary load or runaway processes degrading performance.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2331,"cache_read_input_tokens":111421,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2331},"output_tokens":21,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9f494416-6771-4774-b77c-fe46c3f66807","uuid":"22883b7a-0d24-4a1b-abbc-5efbd2bf1e8f","request_id":"req_011Ccb5uRkmwKFhF7K4M3mzE"}
