{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01StAFfCK91AL8SYRBRYnyKV","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The key insight: ranges 1 and 2 have **lease_holder=2** (node 2 = crdb-cluster-2). The NodeLiveness range is `/System/NodeLiveness-Max`, which might be range 2.\n\nRange 2 is the system NodeLiveness range (r2 in CockroachDB v24.1 maps to `/System/NodeLiveness`). The leaseholder is node 2 (crdb-cluster-2). So all liveness writes go through node 2!\n\nThis means:\n1. When node 2 is down, ALL nodes' liveness heartbeats fail (they all need to write to the liveness range via node 2 as leaseholder)\n2. When node 2 recovers, it has to reacquire the lease for range 2, which slows down all liveness heartbeats during the transition\n\nRange 1 (the meta ranges containing all range descriptors) is also leased by node 2, making it a critical bottleneck—if node 2 struggles, the entire cluster's ability to locate and access ranges degrades. This setup means node 2 controls both the liveness heartbeat mechanism and the metadata routing for every range in the cluster, so any latency issues there cascade everywhere.\n\nThe real puzzle is why node 2 is experiencing 28-30 second write latencies for range 2 specifically. Since all three nodes are replicas and only need a majority for Raft writes, nodes 1 and 3 are healthy and available—so the bottleneck must be something about node 2's own write performance or how it's handling the lease reclamation after restart. nodes 1 and 3 succeed while node 2 fails? Each node writes to its own liveness record within the same range, so the leaseholder processes all writes. But node 2's heartbeat failures are actually epoch increment conflicts—another node incremented node 2's epoch while it was struggling, and now node 2's conditional write to increment it again fails because the epoch was already advanced.\n\nThis creates a retry loop: node 2 fails to heartbeat, another node takes over and increments the epoch, node 2 tries to reclaim it but the conditional put fails, then it waits and retries. The 28-second delay is how long this cycle takes to execute through the Raft pipeline. But if nodes 1 and 3 can successfully write their liveness records to range 2, why is node 2 blocked from doing the same?\n\nThe difference is that nodes 1 and 3 are writing their own records directly, while node 2 is attempting a conditional epoch increment on a record that's being concurrently modified by other nodes—creating a livelock where the conditional write keeps failing. Breaking this cycle requires node 2 to successfully claim its epoch once, which would only happen after the other nodes stop trying to increment it.\n\nBut here's the catch: node 2's liveness keeps expiring before it can write, triggering nodes 1 and 3 to increment the epoch again. The write itself takes 28 seconds, but the timeout is only 3 seconds, so it always fails before completing. This suggests node 2 is the leaseholder of the liveness range, which should make the write fast—so something else is blocking it. Or maybe a stuck proposal in the Raft pipeline from that earlier 60-second block is queuing up all subsequent writes to range 2, causing them to pile up behind it. The stuck proposal would eventually timeout and be abandoned through CockroachDB's normal Raft mechanisms, but until then every write is stuck waiting.\n\nRestarting the node should clear this since the proposer wouldn't remember the old proposal after coming back up, and the other nodes would abandon it when they detect the proposer is gone. But we've already restarted crdb-cluster-2 and the issue persists, which suggests either the stuck proposal somehow got committed and is blocking things in a different way, or this isn't a stuck proposal at all.\n\nLet me check the CPU and memory usage to see if resource contention is starving the writes. Actually, a better approach might be to change the leaseholder for the liveness range from node 2 to node 1 or 3, so node 1 becomes responsible for that range instead. node 1 using `ALTER RANGE ... RELOCATE LEASE TO NODE` if that syntax is available, or I could try draining node 2's leases with the drain command, though that requires node 2 to be responsive enough to handle it. Let me examine the Raft status for range 2 more closely to see what's actually blocking the lease holder.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3296,"cache_read_input_tokens":113752,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3296},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9f494416-6771-4774-b77c-fe46c3f66807","uuid":"66685a63-93ca-4f46-a1c4-38191341b9eb","request_id":"req_011Ccb62RoCr6GihNKCvHjwV"}
